@hachikuji So what's the proposed solution here? I see a couple of options:
1. Increase the timeout here/use a longer timeout for the first poll() so the broker has extra time to create the topic. It's possible we want to do this anyway because it may be too low for a join group cycle to complete with default settings if you have multiple consumers in the group. However, this is just a hack around the real issue, which is that consumer metadata lookup can block for a long time waiting for topic creation. Any code that might interact with a fresh cluster would need similar tweaking.
2. Create the offsets topic proactively. It looks like right now it might only be created upon consumer metadata request. Is there a good reason we can't create it earlier? Then system tests like these could just wait until it's been created before trying to proceed (we can monitor the logs for the relevant output). It also probably provides a better out-of-the-box experience for users -- it's kind of weird to potentially have your first interaction with a cluster as a consumer potentially fail... On the other hand, this fix only works well for system tests because they would _know_ to monitor for that event; new users just running CLI commands wouldn't know about that, so it could still be a problem if the topic takes too long to create.
